text=INCIPIT    LIBER    TERTIUS. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT     I. %0a%0aDE   CONSTRUCTIONE    FABRICS. %0a%0a%0a/1  i^DIFICA  tibi  domum  spatiosam  et  altam,  cujus  longi- %0a•^M^  tudo  ad  orientem  tendatur,  in  cujus  pariete  meridiano %0afacies  fenestras  quot  volueris  et  possis,  ita  ut  inter  duas %0afenestras  quinque  pedes  sint.  Divide  autem  medietatem %0adomus  ad  opus  fusile  faciendum,  et  cuprum  ac  stagnum  et %0aplumbum  operandum,  uno  pariete  usque  ad  summitatem %0aaltitudinis,  et  rursum  divide  quod  reliquum  est  in  duo  in  uno %0apariete,  ad  operandum  in  una  parte  aurum,  in  altera  argentum. %0aFenestrse  vero  non  emineant  altius  a  terra  quam  uno  pede, %0aquarum  altitudo  sit  trium  pedum,  latitudo  duorum. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT    II. %0a%0aDE   SEDE   OPERANTIUM. %0a%0a%0aDEINDE  fode  fossam  ante  fenestram,  a  pariete  fenestras %0apede  et  dlmidio,  quae  stabit  in  transverso,  habens %0alongitudinis  trium  pedum,  latitudinis  duorum,  quam  texes  in %0acircuitu  lignis,  quorum  lignorum  duo  in  medio  contra  fenes- %0atram  procedant  a  fossa  altitudine  dimidii  pedis,  super  quae %0ajungatur  discus  unus  qui  cooperiat  genua  sedentium  in  fossa, %0alatitudine  duorum  pedum,  longitudine  trium,  in  transverso %0asuper  fossam,  ita  esqualis,  ut  quicquid  minutim  auri  vel %0aargenti  desuper  ceciderit,  possit  diligenter  scopari. %0a%0a%0aTHE  BEGINNING %0a%0aOf %0a%0aTHE    THIRD    BOOK. %0a%0a%0aCHAPTER  I. %0a%0aOF   THE   CONSTRUCTION    OF   THE   WORK    BUILDING. %0a%0aBuild  a  spacious  and  lofty  house  for  yourself,  the  length  of %0awhich  must  stretch  towards  the  east ;  in  the  southern  wall  of %0awhich  make  as  many  windows  as  you  wish  and  are  able,  so %0aas  five  feet  may  exist  between  two  windows.  But  separate %0ahalf  of  the  house,  for  making  molten  work,  and  for  working %0acopper,  tin  and  lead,  by  a  wall  reaching  to  the  summit;  and %0aagain  divide  that  part  left  into  two,  by  one  wall,  for  working %0agold  in  one  part,  silver  in  the  other.  The  windows  must  not %0arise  higher  than  a  foot  from  the  ground ;  let  their  height  be %0athree  feet,  their  width  two. %0a%0a%0aCHAPTER  II. %0a%0aOF   THE   SEAT    OF   THE   WORKMEN. %0a%0aThen  dig  a  trench  before  the  window,  a  foot  and  a  half  from %0athe  wall  of  the  window,  which  (trench)  will  stand  across, %0ahaving  the  length  of  three  feet,  the  width  of  two,  which  you %0aline  around  with  wood ;  two  pieces  of  which  wood  can  pro- %0atrude from  the  trench,  in  the  centre  opposite  the  window,  to %0athe  height  of  half  a  foot,  upon  which  a  table,  which  may %0acover  the  knees  of  those  seated  in  the  trench,  is  joined,  in %0abreadth  two  feet,  in  length  three,  crosswise  over  the  trench, %0aso  smooth,  that  whatever  particles  of  gold  or  silver  may  have %0afallen  upon  it  may  be  carefully  collected. %0a%0a%0a210  THEOPHILI    LTBER    III. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT    III. %0a%0aDE   FORNACE   OPERia. %0a%0aJUXTA  parietem  vero  prope  fenestram  in  sinistra  parte %0asedentis,  figatur  ligrnum  in  terram^,  latitudine  duoruro» %0aspissitudine  pene  duorum  digitorum,  quod  cum  firmiter  steterit, %0ahabeat  foramen  grossitudine  unius  digiti  in  medio,  a  terra %0aaltitudine  quatuor  digitorum.  Habeat  quoque  in  anteriore %0aparte  lignum  striatum  sibi  conjunctum,  et  clavis  ligneis  affixum, %0alatitudine  quatuor  digitorum,  cujus  longitudo  sequetur  majori %0aligno.  Ante  quod  stabilies  aliud  lignum  8Bqu8B  latitudinis  et %0alongitudinis,  ita  ut  inter  hsec  duo  ligna  sit  amplitudo  quatuorum %0adigitorum,  et  affige  illud  exterius  duobus  aut  tribus  paxillis, %0aet  accepts  argiUa  non  macerata  nee  aqua  mixta,  sed  noviter %0ae^ossa,  mitte  in  illud  spatium  in  primis  modicum,  et  com- %0apinge  cum  ligno  rotundo  fortiter,  deinde  amplius,  et  iterum %0apercute,  sicque  facies  donee  duee  partes  ipsius  spatii  implean- %0atur,  et  tertiam  dimitte  vacuam.  Tunc  aufer  anterius  lignum, %0aet  cum  cultello  longo  incide  argillam  aequaliter  ante  et  sursum, %0adeinde  cum  gracili  ligno  percute  fortiter.  Post  Iibbc  accipe %0aargillam  maceratam  et  fimo  equi  mixtam,  et  compone  for- %0anacem  et  larem  ejus,  tegens  parietem,  ne  uratur  igne,  et  cum %0agracili  ligno  perfora  argillam  trans  foramen  quod  est  retro  in %0aligno.     Hoc  modo  compone  omnes  fornaces  fabriles. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT    IV. %0a%0a%0aDE    FOLLIBUS. %0a%0a%0aDEINDE  fac  tibi  folles  de  pellibus  arietum  ita.     Cum %0aocciduntur  arietes,  non  incidantur  pelles  sub  ventre,  sed %0ain  posterioribus  aperiantur,  et  ita  eversentur  ut  integree  extra- %0a%0a%0a1  tt %0a%0a%0alongitudine  trium  pedum,"    Bx  MS.  Ouelph. %0a%0a%0aTRANSLATION.  211 %0a%0aCHAPTER  in. %0a%0aOP   THE    WORK    FURNACE. %0a%0aNear  the  wall,  by  the  window,  on  the  left  side  of  the  person %0asitting,  a  piece  of  wood  is  fixed  in  the  ground  (three  *  feet  in %0alength)  in  width  two  and  in  thickness  scarcely  two  fingers, %0awhich,  when  it  is  firmly  fixed,  may  have  a  perforation  in  the %0amidst  of  the  size  of  a  finger,  four  fingers  high  above  the %0aground.  Let  it  have  also  in  front  a  straight  piece  of  wood %0ajoined  to  it,  and  fixed  with  wooden  pegs,  four  fingers  in %0abreadth,  and  the  length  of  which  is  equal  to  the  large  piece %0aof  wood.  In  front  of  this  you  fasten  another  wood  of  equal %0abreadth  and  length,  so  that  between  these  two  woods  there %0amay  be  a  space  of  four  fingers,  and  fasten  that  outside  by  two %0aor  three  stakes ;  and  taking  clay,  not  beaten,  nor  mixed,  with %0awater,  but  newly  dug  up,  put  at  first  a  little  of  it  into  this %0aspace,  and  compress  it  strongly  with  a  rounded  piece  of  wood, %0athen  more,  and  again  beat  it ;  and  do  thus  until  two  parts  of %0athis  space  are  filled,  and  leave  the  third  empty.  Then  take %0aaway  the  wood  in  front,  and  with  a  long  knife  cut  the  clay %0aevenly  in  front  and  on  the  top,  then  with  a  thin  piece  of  wood %0abeat  it  strongly.  After  this  take  clay  beaten  and  mixed  with %0ahorse  dung,  and  make  the  furnace  and  its  hearth,  covering %0athe  wall  that  it  may  not  be  burned  by  the  fire,  and  with  a %0aslender  piece  of  wood  perforate  the  clay  through  the  opening %0awhich  is  in  the  wood  behind.  In  this  manner  compose  all %0asmith's  furnaces. %0a%0a%0aCHAPTER  IV. %0a%0a%0aOF   THE   BELLOWS. %0a%0a%0aThen  make  bellows  from  the  skins  of  rams,  thus  : — When  the %0arams  are  killed,  the  skins  must  not  be  cut  under  the  belly, %0abut  they  are  opened  behind,  and  are  so  turned  over  that  they %0a%0a*  From,  t/ie  Wolfenbuikl  Manuscript. %0a%0ap  2 %0a%0a%0a212  THEOPHILI    LIBER    III. %0a%0ahantur,  et  impletse  stramine  modice  exsiccentur.  PoBtea  jaceant %0ain  confectione  iaecis  et  salis  una  die  et  duabus  noctibus^  tertia %0a▼ero  die  trahantur  in  retorta  in  longitudine,  sed  plus  in  lati- %0atudine.  Deinde  ungantur  et  iteruin  trahantur.  Posthsec %0afiat  foUi  caput  ligneum,  quod  transeat  per  coUum  ejus  et %0aibi  ligetur,  et  in  capite  foramen  per  quod  transeat  fistula %0aferrea.  Retro  vero  in  latitudine  folHs  ponantur  quatuor  ligna, %0aquorum  duo  sibi  conjungantur  et  coUigentur  in  medio,  et  duo %0asibi  deinde  suantur  in  folle  ita,  ut  juncturse  in  medio  sint  su- %0aperius  et  inferius,  ubi  etiam  duse  ansae  ex  eadem  pelie  con- %0asuantur,  una  superius  minor,  in  qua  poUex  imponatur,  altera %0amajor  inferius,  ubi  reliqui  quatuor  digiti  immittantur.  His %0acompletis  pone  fistulam  ferream  in  foramen  fomacis,  et  retro %0aet  ante  fornacem  carbones  et  ignem,  et  suffla  ut  fomax  exsic- %0acetur.  Utensiliorum  autem  et  ferramentorum  nomina  in  fabrili %0aopere  sunt  bsec. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT    V. %0a%0aDE    INCUDIBUS. %0a%0aINCUDES  latse,  eequales  et  quadree.  Item  incudes  sequales %0aet  comutse.  Item  incudes  superius  rotundae  in  similitudine %0adimidii  pomi,  una  major,  alia  minor,  tertia  brevis,  qui  vocan- %0atur  nodi.  Item  incudes  superius  longaa  et  strictsB  quasi  duo %0acomua  ab  hastili  prsecedentia,  quorum  unum  sit  rotundum  et %0adeductum  ita,  ut  in  summitate  sit  gracile,  aliud  vero  latius  et %0ain  summitate  modice  recurvum  in  rotunda  sequalitate  ad %0asimilitudinem  imius  pollicis.  Hae  sunt  majores  et  minores. %0a%0a%0aTRANSLATION.  213 %0a%0amay  be  stripped  off  whole,  and  being  filled  with  straw,  they %0aare  moderately  dried.  Afterwards  they  are  thrown  into  a %0apreparation  of  lye  and  salt  for  a  day  and  two  nights,  the %0athird  day  they  are  stretched  lengthwise,  but  more  in  breadth. %0aThen  they  are  anointed  and  again  stretched.  After  this  the %0awooden  head  to  the  bellows  is  made,  which  passes  through %0aits  neck  and  is  there  bound,  and  in  this  head  a  perforation %0athrough  which  an  iron  tube  may  pass.  But  behind,  in  the %0awidth  of  the  bellows,  four  pieces  of  wood  are  placed,  of  which %0atwo  are  joined  together  and  fixed  in  the  middle ;  and  two  are %0asewed  upon  the  bellows  together,  so  that  the  joinings  in %0athe  middle  may  be  above  and  below ;  where  also  two  loops %0aof  the  same  skin  are  sewed  on,  the  one  above  smaller^  in %0awhich  the  thumb  is  placed,  the  other  larger  below,  where  the %0aother  four  fingers  are  put.  These  things  finished,  place  the %0airon  tube  in  the  hole  of  the  furnace,  and  fire  and  charcoal  at %0athe  back  and  front  of  the  furnace,  and  blow,  that  the  furnace %0amay  become  dry.  The  names  of  utensils  and  iron  instru- %0aments, in  work  of  fusion,  are  these. %0a%0a%0aCHAPTER  V, %0a%0a%0aOF   ANVILS. %0a%0a%0aAnvils,  flat,  smooth  and  square.  Also  anvils  even  and %0ahomed.  Also  anvils  round  at  the  top,  like  half  an  apple,  one %0alarge,  another  smaller,  a  third  short,  which  are  called  knots. %0aAlso  anvils  long  and  narrow  on  the  top,  like  two  horns  pro- %0aceeding from  a  spear,  of  which  one  may  be  rounded  and %0adiminishing  so  that  it  be  pointed  at  the  end,  but  the  other %0abroader  and  slightly  turned  round  at  the  end  with  round %0asmoothness,  like  a  thumb.  These  are  made  large  and %0asmall. %0a%0a%0a214  THEOPIIILI    LIBKR    III. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT   VI. %0a%0a%0aDK    MALLEI8. %0a%0a%0aMALLEI  multi,  inajores,  minores  et  parvi,  in  una  parte %0alati,  in  altera  stricti.  Item  mallei  longi  et  graciles  in %0asummitate  rotundi,  majores  et  minores.  Item  mallei  superius %0acornuti^  inferius  lati. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT   VII. %0a%0aDB    FORCIPIBUS. %0a%0aFORCIPES  manual es  fortes,  habentes  nodos  in  summi- %0atate, majores  et  minores.  Item  Torcipes  longi  et  gra- %0aciles. Item  forcipes  fusorii  longi,  et  in  anteriori  parte  modi- %0acum curvi.  Item  forcipes  mediocres,  quibus  limanda  quseque %0ateneantur,  qui  sint  in  summitate  unius  caudae  graciles,  in %0aaltera  pendeat  ferrum  tenue  et  latum,  ac  perforatum,  cui  cum %0aposueris  aliquid  parvum  limandum,  comprime  fortiter,  et %0amitte  gracilem  caudam  in  quod  foramen  volueris.  Item  for- %0acipes parvuli,  in  una  summitate  sibi  adhserentes,  et  in  altera %0agraciles,  quibus  grana  et  alia  quseque  minuta  componantur. %0aItem  forcipes,  qui  dicuntur  carbonarii,  et  majores  et  minores, %0aquse  sint  in  una  summitate  integri  et  plicati,  in  altera  aperti  et %0amodice  curvi.  Item  forcipes  incisorii  majores  et  minores,  in %0aduabus  parti  bus  compositi  et  clavo  confixi. %0a%0a%0aCAPUT   VIII. %0a%0aDE   FERRIS    PER   QUJE    FILA   TRAHUNTUR. %0a%0aFERRI  duo  latitudine  trium  digitorum,  superius  et  inferius %0astricti,  per  omnia  tenues,  et  tribus  ordinibus  aut  quatuor %0aperforati,  per  quae  foramina  fila  trahantur. %0a%0a%0aTRANSLATION.  216 %0a%0aCHAPTER  VI. %0a%0aOF    HAMMERS. %0a%0aMany  hammers,  Isii'gCy  middling  and  small,  at  one  end  flat, %0aat  the  other  narrow.  Also  long  and  slender  hammers  rotind %0aat  the  end,  large  and  small.  Also  hammers  homed  at  th^ %0atop,  wide  at  the  bottom. %0a%0a%0aCHAPTER  Vn. %0a%0aOP   PINCERS. %0a%0a%0aStrong  hand  pincers,  having  knobs  at  the  top,  large  and  smaller. %0aAlso  long  and  slender  pincers.  Also  founders'  pincers,  long %0aand  slightly  curved  at  the  upper  end.  Also  pincers  of  mode- %0arate size,  with  which  any  things  to  be  filed  are  held,  which %0amust  be  slender  at  the  top  of  one  of  the  branches,  and  at  the %0aother  must  hang  a  thin  and  broad  piece  of  iron,  and  perfo- %0arated, in  which  when  you  place  any  thing  small  for  filing %0ayou  press  strongly,  and  place  the  slender  branch  in  any %0aopening  you  please.  Also  yery  small  pincers  united  to- %0agether at  one  extremity  and  slender  at  the  other,  with  which %0abeads  and  other  minute  things  are  arranged  together.  Also %0apincers  which  are  called  coal-pincers,  both  large  and  small, %0awhich  must  be  entire  and  bent  at  one  end,  open  and  slightly %0acurved  at  the  other.  Also  cutting  pincers,  large  and  small, %0amade  in  two  parts,  and  fastened  together  by  a  rivet. %0a%0a%0aCHAPTER  VIII. %0a%